			<div class="content" id="post-content-2379598">
									

<p>Ideally that would be the case, but we don't live in an ideal world. There are a few things that I think make firsts different:</p>
<ul>
<li>Readers don't have any expectations based on the author's previous work. This probably results in less patience for anything difficult or novel.</li>
<li>The draft is less likely to attract feedback based on reciprocity (unless the author has given good feedback to several drafts prior to writing their own work) and can't attract feedback based on association with prior work.</li>
<li>Authors are likely to be more anxious about sharing first work.</li>
<li>Authors have less experience and relationships with the community, and therefore can't use the resources as fully as an experienced author.</li>
<li>Authors have less experience with the format, wiki syntax and other technical aspects that take some practice.</li>
</ul>

