<p>I completely agree. It honestly shouldn't matter if it's a first work or not. I actually don't think it does.</p>
<p>However, I do believe new authors end up feeling one of two things: either the first SCP will suck and be deleted, or the first SCP must become one of the best on the site. Neither is true. There are plenty of successful first articles on the site.</p>
<p>And, like I mention above, it's fully possible to fall into negatives but still save the article and have it enter positives in the end. It takes actual hard work and critical thinking in order to do that, but it can be done, and I've seen it happen.</p>
<p>In the end, the new author should not believe that if they aren't an incredible author already, their first article will fail. This is simply not true. It's just that one can't just throw up any random thought on the wiki and expect it to last. It's got to be carefully crafted.</p>

