															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/dankaar" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1790336); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1790336&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610251601" alt="dankaar" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1790336)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/dankaar" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1790336); return false;" >dankaar</a></span> <span class="odate time_1442880036 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">22 Sep 2015 00:00</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2379613">
									

<p>Mine is <a href="/scp-2207">SCP-2207</a>. I submitted it on 08/03/15, and it reached +89 by 08/31/15, ending up as the top-rated page for that month.</p>
<p>Making things more difficult (for me) was the fact that the actual inspiration is #11 from <a href="/the-big-list-of-overdone-scp-cliches">The Big List of Overdone SCP Cliches</a>. It's a knife what cuts through dimensions. It can't get any more basic than that.</p>
<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">How&nbsp;did&nbsp;I&nbsp;do&nbsp;it?</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">I'll&nbsp;tell&nbsp;ya!</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<p>Part of what helped it be successful was that I was, for over a year, an active commentator and critiquer. I ended up internalizing many aspects of what people pointed out as a good or bad SCP, and kept coming back to the lowest rated pages, seeing how and where articles stumbled.</p>
<p>I also made it a point to read all of the guides. Not in one sitting, mind you, but over time.</p>
<p>During that time, I wrote up drafts for other things, and getting them reviewed on the forums, but never submitted them. They were lagely practice in the format. Keep this in mind: making a Successful First SCP is not the same as your First SCP Idea. Knowing what Ideas are good to start with, and which ones you have a good chance at pulling off is key. You won't know this at first, but if you join in discussions and practice the format (while getting feedback), you'll get a better idea of what you can do.</p>
<p>I didn't work much on the idea until I heard that the Short Works Contest was a thing. I took the basic concept, &quot;knife what cuts through dimensions&quot;, and ruminated on what it could mean. In this case, &quot;dimension&quot; could easily mean &quot;alternate reality&quot; and &quot;cut through&quot; more-or-leas means &quot;severed&quot;. Hence, a knife that severs alternate realities, and took that to it's logical conclusion (destroying a universe).</p>
<p>Once I had the idea ready, I moved it to the Drafts forum, and then Chat (both #site19 and #site17). In Chat, I listened to the feedback, with most reviewers expressing interest in what happened during the testing phase, or giving a generic &quot;It's missing something&quot; reviews. Keep in mind, at the time I didn't have the collapsed section on 2207 that is there now, so as to meet the wordcount limit for the Short Works Contest.</p>
<p>So, I shifted gears and expanded the idea to include logs. This is another tip: you should listen to feedback if multiple people tell you to change or improve something, <em>even if doing so significantly alters what you had planned</em>. It's easier to work with the grain than against it, and trying to go down a route that multiple people are indicating that won't work will more likely fail than suceed.</p>
<p>After adding the logs, I once again went to chat for reviews, as many as I could get for about a week or two. Once multiple people said that they couldn't find anything wrong or anything to modify, I posted. This is an important tip: don't post until the majority of people over a period of time say that they can't find anything wrong with it. One person's opinion won't match with everyone else; only a poll of multiple people can show how well an article is posting.</p>
<p>Only then did I post, after using Microsoft Word to replace my number placeholder for the actual number.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>So, my tips:</p>
<ul>
<li>Get involved in the forums and critiques. The more you understand how a SCP works or fails, the better you will be prepared for when you start writing.</li>
<li>Don't be too afraid to post a draft. It's practice in the worst-case scenario, and you can see where your strengths and weaknessed are.</li>
<li>Don't always go with your first idea. Related to the above point, you might find that it won't work, or you lack the skill to pull it off at the time. This is not a bad thing, everyone produces a lemon now and again.</li>
<li>Always listen to feedback, especially when multiple people say the same thing. Chances are, it will steer you to a more &quot;correct&quot; way to create your article that plays to its strengths, even if they aren't what you intended.</li>
<li>You're ready to post when (almost) everyone can't see flaws or ways to improve it, but not saying that it's missing something.</li>
</ul>
<p>&#8230; Yeah, some of those are generic SCP writing tips, but keep in mind that the biggest difficulty with a First SCP is the inexperience of the writer.</p>

							</div>

								
					
