															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/psul" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2156983); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=2156983&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610251601" alt="psul" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=2156983)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/psul" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2156983); return false;" >psul</a></span> <span class="odate time_1442909195 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">22 Sep 2015 08:06</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2379722">
									

<p><a href="/scp-2130">SCP-2130</a> was my first posted article, and one of the ones that WJS cites as surviving initial downvotes. As <a href="http://www.scp-wiki.net/psuls-author-page">my author page</a> relates, it sat at -7 for some time, before slowly clawing its way back to the low positives.</p>
<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">+&nbsp;How&nbsp;I&nbsp;wrote&nbsp;it</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">-&nbsp;collapse</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<ul>
<li>This was not the first draft I posted on the site. My first idea (which eventually became <a href="/scp-2138">SCP-2138</a>) got a very heavy critique from Eskobar on the forums, and I realised that I needed more time and practice before writing it up, as it had some tricky story mechanics.</li>
<li>Having read the guides, I deliberately chose something that was not Keter, not humanoid, and wouldn't require an image. I searched the site to see if there was something similar in existence already, and didn't find anything.</li>
<li>I am not particularly good at eliciting feedback in chat, so posted to the forum. I was lucky: Mister Ious gave me two line-by-lines and some good overall thoughts within the space of 3 days.</li>
<li>I was not very patient - I went from first forum draft to post within 5 days. I suspect that I could have obtained additional feedback by waiting a little longer.</li>
<li>When posting, I took a long time and triple-checked every step in the &quot;How to post&quot; part of the guide. I made a few last-minute changes when proof-reading before posting.</li>
<li>Immediately after posting, I put in an author post, and then announced. I do think that an initial author post can be a way to set the tone for the discussion to follow (although I didn't use it for that purpose in this case).</li>
<li>The post went up late at night for me, and I woke up to a spate of downvotes. I was very disappointed, and struggled not to take it personally. Before responding to the comments, I tried to work out the core of what people objected to (which was the kappa radiation, and the tone of my final note). I realised they had a point, and made some amendments before replying - trying to justify the k-rays, and fixing the note.</li>
<li>The (relatively minor) changes I made were enough to stabilise the voting, so I left it, and it slowly crept upwards before settling at +5. It was a lesson that the margins between downvotes and upvotes can sometimes be pretty slim.</li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">+&nbsp;What&nbsp;I&nbsp;learned</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">-&nbsp;collapse</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<ul>
<li>Even though I'd read the guides, I probably wasn't sufficiently familiar with what the site was looking for in terms of writing. I had seen a reasonable number of down-voted SCPs, but I hadn't yet seen lots of current, upvoted SCPs. As such, it was easy to assume that the downvotes were for technical writing issues (formatting, grammar, tone) rather than structural story-telling issues (strength and development of ideas).</li>
<li>Like sirpudding, I agree that there are disadvantages to launching a first idea with too high a degree of difficulty. That's not a reason to write something that is very similar to existing skips, but if you've only been on a site for a month or less, chances are you don't appreciate how good world-building has to be to succeed. I would hesitate now to write something with &quot;new Humes&quot; (in the form of kappa radiation) or an O5 note. While I was writing in a slightly meta way about lolFoundation tropes, I also hadn't appreciated that any reference to them would cause issues for some readers (even though Mister Ious pointed that out in the forum).</li>
<li>Generally, the people who will read (and vote on) your skip first will be the users that are constantly updating the site for new content. That means they read lots of bad skips, and will be quite quick on the downvote button. The good news is that they are also more likely to respond if the author engages with their comments and amends the post, so those votes are easier to turn around in the early going. If the post survives 24 hours at higher than -5, the flood of downvotes tends to taper off, so generally you will have at least a few more days' survival time in order to fix it, if it's fixable. Of course, ideally you'll have received all of that feedback before posting.</li>
<li>When thinking about how to fix a failing post, the temptation is to throw in everyone's suggestions as quickly as possible. However that can be counter-productive, and lead to oversteer - I have several times seen people lose what made their idea interest in the first place in an attempt to appease reviewers. In my case, while lots of people suggested deleting kappa radiation (and while that might be the right idea in the long run) I couldn't see a convincing way of doing that in real time without undermining the anomaly I'd set up. The risk was that I would have a poorly-thought-out replacement idea written up in a rush, and that would make the post worse, instead of better. As it is, a few small changes allowed it to survive (at least until I drew everyone's attention to it just now!) and I may be able to re-write it when time and inspiration allow.</li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>
</div>

