															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/wrongjohnsilver" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2000367); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=2000367&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610251601" alt="WrongJohnSilver" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=2000367)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/wrongjohnsilver" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2000367); return false;" >WrongJohnSilver</a></span> <span class="odate time_1443108267 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">24 Sep 2015 15:24</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2380864">
									

<p>Well, I started the thread, I should probably write about my experiences with <a href="/scp-2289">SCP-2289</a>.</p>
<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">+&nbsp;This&nbsp;is&nbsp;my&nbsp;story.</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">-&nbsp;And&nbsp;go&nbsp;forth&nbsp;and&nbsp;practice.</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<p>Although SCP-2289 was my first SCP, it wasn't my first draft or my first submission. My first draft was for a skip I called History Of The World. It consisted of a giant scroll from Alexandria that appeared to contain the entire history of everyone, up until modern times (although no one had yet managed to unfurl the scroll that far, and they were nearing the end of the scroll). It was supposed to be an <em>editable</em> history, but I had buried the lede so deep it wasn't clear, even though <a href="/scp-507">SCP-507</a> stopped in to make a correction, and one year around the Mediterranean was heavily adjusted and redacted haphazardly (in a buried reference to <a href="/scp-1751">SCP-1751</a>). I put up a forum draft and realized I didn't describe things well enough, invoked a famous skip for a blessing, etc. It was pretty well torn apart, and I just let that sit for a while.</p>
<p>Then, the reimagining contest came about, and I revisited the idea of retrocausality with my tale <a href="/it-s-just-a-dream">It's Just A Dream</a>, which did well, I think, for a first submission.</p>
<p>After that, I set out to write and submit a new SCP idea, which eventually became SCP-2289, which I like because it's not just body horror, it's cute and refreshing body horror.</p>
<p>Here's my advice for new authors, based on my efforts.</p>
<ul>
<li>Read the guides. Use the sandbox. Post in the forums. This is KEY to being able to make something that lasts.</li>
<li>Remember that if someone completely misses the point of an article, it's most likely the author's fault. So, if someone says something doesn't work, and interprets it completely wrong, don't think, &quot;Oh, they just don't know what they're talking about.&quot; Instead, think, &quot;I wonder how they came up with that conclusion? What did I write to make that a possibility?&quot;</li>
<li>Be aware that not everyone is going to like your stylistic choices, and that's okay, as long as enough other people do. 2289 lost votes because I mentioned <a href="/scp-173">SCP-173</a>, but it also gained some because of it. Also, some people took issue with SCP-2289-7's mode of speech, but as long as you're speaking from experience, it will show through as honest.</li>
<li>Don't worry about making the biggest and baddest thing. Something that isn't inexorably deadly can be far more interesting. You want to interact with it, not run away.</li>
<li>The Special Containment Procedures are golden. They give the reader a chance to interact with something before even knowing what it is. And when they don't know yet, you can write fun zingers like, &quot;Any lack of appetite or difficulty swallowing observed in any organisms within containment must be immediately brought to the attention of Site-66's veterinarian surgeon, who will assess whether emergency ocular removal is necessary.&quot; What, they're not eating, so you have to tear its eye out? What's going on? This is where you get to soften and disorient the reader. Treasure that.</li>
<li>Also, research, research, research! I read through a TON before posting 2289. First, I had my first draft, realized I was doing it wrong, and accepted the fact I needed to learn more about what works. Second, I read up on Devil Facial Tumor Disease, understood how it worked, how it spread, and how it killed. Third, I went through the contagion and ocular tags to make sure I hadn't come up with an idea that had been done before. Yes, I didn't see any Devil Facial Tumor Disease, but I also read over skips like <a href="/scp-378">SCP-378</a>, <a href="/scp-253">SCP-253</a>, and <a href="/scp-718">SCP-718</a> and made sure my idea was different enough from those. Finally, I spent time thinking about what would happen, what would not happen, how to show it all, how to talk about it. That's why the interview is so important in that skip&#8212;it's a way to understand what's happening while allowing you to break tone as needed. You want everything to make sense. You don't have to share all your research, but you do want to know the answer to, &quot;what would happen if I did this?&quot;</li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>
</div>

