			<div class="content" id="post-content-2380947">
									

<blockquote>
<p>Remember that if someone completely misses the point of an article, it's most likely the author's fault. So, if someone says something doesn't work, and interprets it completely wrong, don't think, &quot;Oh, they just don't know what they're talking about.&quot; Instead, think, &quot;I wonder how they came up with that conclusion? What did I write to make that a possibility?&quot;</p>
</blockquote>
<p>I think this is tricky, because it is easy to over explain in response to readers who aren't understanding or are misunderstanding. I did this with my second article, <a href="/scp-2890">SCP-2890</a>, before I paired it back in response to post-mainlist feedback, and I think it is clear from the discussion pages for my first <a href="/scp-2323">SCP-2323</a> and my fifth (and currently least popular) <a href="/scp-2140">SCP-2140</a> that some people had trouble getting either of those. Given that <a href="/scp-2323">SCP-2323</a> only has three downvotes and the changes those readers asked for would have totally changed the article (by replacing the anomaly with a completely different type of anomaly), in that case I feel confident that accepting that some people didn't get it is the right move. For <a href="/scp-2140">SCP-2140</a> It is more ambiguous, but the limitations of the contest rules made expanding it impossible, and now it is rated high enough that I am hesitant to change anything.</p>
<p>I guess what I am saying is: listen to the people who say they don't get it and try to see what it is that you wrote that is causing confusion, but don't ignore the people who say they do get it. Consider that if writing to the former you will alienate the latter.</p>

							</div>

								
